Test specs (H.1 additions):
  1. "poll sweep: claim phase uses FOR UPDATE SKIP LOCKED inside
      sql.begin + bumps next_poll_at lease before adapter runs"
        - Drives a one-row sweep against an unknowntoolkit (no
          adapter) so the no-adapter branch is exercised after the
          claim.
        - Asserts the SELECT fragment contains "FROM
          public.composio_poll_state" AND "FOR UPDATE SKIP LOCKED".
        - Asserts a tentative-lease UPDATE (interval '1 second',
          no last_polled_at) fires AFTER the SELECT.
        - Asserts the UPDATE-lease index in sqlCalls is greater
          than the SELECT-claim index (order critical to the
          locking contract).
  2. "two parallel sweeps: each ID is claimed by EXACTLY one
      invocation (FOR UPDATE SKIP LOCKED contract)"
        - Smart mock for sql tag tracks a shared `claimed` Set; the
          SELECT-FOR-UPDATE-SKIP-LOCKED returns up to 2 of the 4
          unclaimed rows per call, mutating the Set inside the tag.
        - Invokes pollComposioTriggers twice via Promise.all.
        - Asserts scanned counts sum to 4 AND claimed.size === 4
          (no double-claim).
        - Reviewer noted this models call shape, not the DB-level
          invariant — live e2e (deferred / matches H.4) is the
          definitive test.

Behavior contract:
  ✓ Claim transaction is atomic: SELECT-FOR-UPDATE + UPDATE-lease
    in one sql.begin block. Row locks release on commit; the lease
    keeps rows invisible to subsequent sweeps until either (a) the
    adapter writes the real next_poll_at on success/failure or (b)
    300s pass.
  ✓ Adapter-completion UPDATEs (success, failure-backoff, pause,
    no-adapter) all overwrite the lease with the real next_poll_at
    (or paused_at). No lease-residue bug on the active paths.
  ✓ Lambda-killed-mid-adapter scenario: lease keeps rows invisible
    for up to 300s; after lease expires, another sweep picks them
    up. Adapter's defensive-recovery branches (every adapter F.3-
    F.8 has one) handle the re-fetch idempotently.
  ✓ Supavisor :6543 transaction-mode pooler supports multi-
    statement BEGIN/COMMIT (that is the literal purpose of
    transaction-mode pooling). The earlier memory about :6543 was
    specific to LISTEN state, not BEGIN/COMMIT. postgres-js's
    prepare:false (already set) avoids the prepared-statement
    incompatibility.
  ✓ `id = ANY(${ids}::uuid[])` is the documented postgres-js idiom
    for array parameter binding with cast.

Adversarial review (review-1.json):
  Opus 4.7 via Agent tool; verdict: ship; 0 blockers; 5 nits.
  Nits:
    - pause UPDATE leaves the 5-min lease in next_poll_at
      (harmless under current `paused_at IS NULL` filter; would
      bite if an operator clears paused_at to unpause)
    - TENTATIVE_LEASE_SECONDS=300 is longer than typical Lambda
      timeout — document relationship
    - Test #2 smart-mock models call shape, not true DB lock
      contention
    - POLL_TENTATIVE_LEASE_SECONDS env override absent from spec
      text
    - Explicit `const due: Array<DueRow>` annotation would harden
      against future refactor

Notes / decisions:
  - Tentative lease = 5 minutes. Generous vs typical adapter
    duration (~300ms-15s with H.2) but bounded so a crashed Lambda
    doesn't starve a row forever. Configurable via
    POLL_TENTATIVE_LEASE_SECONDS env for tests + emergency tuning.
  - Decided NOT to roll back the lease on Lambda death via a
    dead-letter mechanism — adapter idempotency + lease expiry is
    simpler and matches the eventual-consistency posture of the
    sweep.

Out of scope (lands in H.2+):
  - H.2: per-adapter 15s timeout + per-row error isolation
  - H.3: per-workspace fairness via ROW_NUMBER window
  - H.4: throughput — batch size 100 + Lambda self-invocation chain
  - H.5: per-workspace Composio rate-limit guard
  - H.6: Lambda memory bump + reservedConcurrency + EMF metrics
  - H.7: live load test (100 synthetic triggers)
